"'''A Million Miles Away'''" is a song by [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] recording artist [[Rihanna]] from her second [[studio album]], ''[[A Girl Like Me (Rihanna album)|A Girl like Me]]'' (2006). It was written and produced by [[Evan Rogers]] and [[Carl Sturken]]. It was recorded at The Loft Recording Studios in [[Bronxville, New York]] and at [[Conway Recording Studios]] in [[Hollywood, California]]. A multitude of musicians and instruments were used for the song's instrumental, which includes piano, guitar, cello, percussion, violo and strings. "A Million Miles Away" is an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Pop music|pop]] [[ballad]], which also incorporates elements of [[dance-pop]] and [[Urban music|urban]]. The song garnered a mixed reaction from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. While some critics praised Rihanna for avoiding a [[sophomore slump]] by having better material than her debut album, ''[[Music of the Sun]]'' (2005), others criticized the song for being bland. In November 2009, three and a half years after the release of ''A Girl like Me'', "A Million Miles Away" charted at number 38 on the Spanish singles chart, although Rihanna had released two albums since its release, ''[[Good Girl Gone Bad]]'' (2007) and ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' (2009).

==Recording and composition==
"A Million Miles Away" was written and produced by [[Evan Rogers]] and [[Carl Sturken]] for Syndicated Rhythm Productions.<ref name="Notes">{{cite album-notes|artist=Rihanna|title=[[A Girl like Me (Rihanna album)|A Girl Like Me]]|year=2006|format= inlay cover|publisher= [[The Island Def Jam Music Group]]|publisherid=0602517170483}}</ref> It was recorded by Al Hemberger at The Loft Recording Studios in [[Bronxville, New York]] and at [[Conway Recording Studios]] in [[Hollywood, California]].<ref name="Notes"/> The assistant recording engineer for the process was Sam Holland.<ref name="Notes"/> It was [[Mixing (music production)|mixed]] by Hemberger at The Loft Recording Studios.<ref name="Notes"/> [[Strings (instrument)|Strings]] were arranged and conducted by Rob Mounsey, [[violins]] were provided for by Ann Leathers (who served as the [[Concertmaster]]), as well as Richard Sortomme, Cenovia Cummins, Uri Vodovoz, Jan Mullen, Jeanne Ingram, Abe Appleman, Katherine Livosli-Stern, Maura Gianni, Yana Goichman and Marti Sweet.<ref name="Notes"/> Rogers and Sturken performed the [[piano]] and the [[guitar]], while Ted Hermberger performed the [[percussion]].<ref name="Notes"/> [[Violas]] were performed by Sue Pray, Crystal Garner, Jill Jaffe and Mary Hamman.<ref name="Notes"/> Richard Locker, Gene Moy and Eugene Briskin performed the [[cello]] while John Beal and Judy Sugarman provided the [[Bass (instrument)|bass]].<ref name="Notes"/> Debbie Mounsey servered as the production assisstant.<ref name="Notes"/>

"A Million Miles Away" is an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name="IGN">{{cite web|url=http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/709/709419p1.html|title=Rihanna <U+2013> A Girl Like Me|publisher=[[IGN]]. [[News Corporation]]|date=June 18, 2006|accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref> and [[Pop music|pop]] inspired [[ballad]].<ref name="TWPReview">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/25/AR2006042501896.html|title=Quick Spin|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> It also contains elements of [[dance-pop]] and [[Urban contemporary|urban]] genres.<ref name="Musicnotes">{{cite web|url=|title=A Girl Like Me &ndash; Rihanna Digital Music Sheet|work=''Musicnotes.com''|publisher=[[Peer International (music publishing)|Peer International Music Publishing]]|productnumber=MN0072687 (Product Number)|year=2006|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref> The song is written in the key of [[D major]] and is set in [[common time]] with a [[Tempo|slow feel]] of 64 [[Beats per minute#Beats per minute|beats per minute]].<ref name="Musicnotes">{{cite web|url=|title=A Girl Like Me &ndash; Rihanna Digital Music Sheet|work=''Musicnotes.com''|publisher=[[Peer International (music publishing)|Peer International Music Publishing]]|productnumber=MN0072687 (Product Number)|year=2006|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref> Rihanna's vocal range in the song spans two [[Octave|octaves]] from the low note of [[C (musical note)|C]]<sub>3</sub> to the high note of [[D (musical note)|D]]<sub>5</sub>.<ref name="Musicnotes"/> The song lasts for a duration of four minutes and nine seconds.<ref name="iTunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/a-girl-like-me/id171762971|title=Rihanna &ndash; A Girl Like Me|work=''[[iTunes Store]] (US)''|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref>

==Critical reception==
Dan Charnas for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' was complimentary of Rihanna's ability to avoid a "sophomore slump" with ''A Girl like Me'' by including songs on the album which were just as good, if not better, than songs present on her debut album ''[[Music of the Sun]]'' (2005).<ref name="TWPReview"/> He wrote that she "digs into some pretty ambitious pop ballads" and wrote that "A Million Miles Away" would become a song "tangled" by future ''[[American Idol|American Idols]]''.<ref name="TWPReview"/> Quentin B. Huff for [[Popmatters]] was critical of the song, writing that "A Million Miles Away", along with "[[Unfaithful (song)|Unfaithful]]", were not as good as "Final Goodbye", writing {{" '}}Final Goodbye' has more going for it than 'Unfaithful' or the final ballad, 'A Million Miles Away'."<ref name="PopMattersReview">{{cite web|last=Huff|first=Quentin B.|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/rihanna-a-girl-like-me/|title=Review: A Girl Like Me|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|date=April 25, 2006|accessdate=A 2012}}</ref> He continued to admit that although "A Million Miles Away" and "Unfaithful" were not "bad songs", he stated "Rihanna best demonstrates her immense talent when she plays to her strength with songs that favor her island roots."<ref name="PopMattersReview"/> Spencer D. for [[IGN]] wrote that "A Million Miles Away" was one of the songs on the album which follows a "somewhat standard New School R&B tactic", and that it is a "straight ahead contemporary ballad."<ref name="IGN"/> He continued to say that Rihanna sounds better when she restrains her voice instead of pushing it to her limit.<ref name="IGN"/> Sal Cinquemani for [[Slant Magazine]] was critical of the song, along with "Final Goodbye", writing that they are "gooey and spineless slow numbers" which "kill whatever momentum the album has."<ref name="Slant">{{cite news|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/rihanna-a-girl-like-me/794|title=Rihanna: A Girl Like Me|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=April 24, 2006|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref>

